        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The following example creates a simple <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph> and a <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.Button&gt;</ph>:</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.Primitives.ButtonBase.Click&gt;</ph> event handler of the button contains logic to sort the items in the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph> in the descending order.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>You can do this because adding items to a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph> this way adds them to the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ItemCollection&gt;</ph> of the <ph id="ph3">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph>, and <ph id="ph4">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ItemCollection&gt;</ph> derives from the <ph id="ph5">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Data.CollectionView&gt;</ph> class.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>If you are binding your <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ListBox&gt;</ph> to a collection using the <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.ItemsControl.ItemsSource%2A&gt;</ph> property, you can use the same technique to sort.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>As long as you have a reference to the view object, you can use the same technique to sort the content of other collection views.</source>
        </trans-unit>
